{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"47d8be472a62e033a34ab7f54e5875ee1a1f0e6dec0aae2580329b4b547064fd","slug":"xradioandcheckboxes","location":"/xRadioandCheckBoxes.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Radio and Check Boxes","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"James Goudy","given":"James","family":"Goudy"},"name":"James Goudy","id":"contributors-a_books\\csci211_csbook\\myst-generated-uid-0"}],"github":"https://github.com/executablebooks/jupyter-book","keywords":["JavaScript","TypeScript"],"copyright":"2026","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"xRadioandCheckBoxes.md","url":"/build/xRadioandCheckBoxes-d938eadaa7b2d94ab3c3f141e189781d.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Radio buttons and checkboxes are two of the most common ways a web page collects “choice” input, but they behave very differently: radios enforce a single decision inside a shared group (only one option can be selected at a time), while checkboxes allow multiple independent selections (zero, one, or many). This example demonstrates both patterns in one clean page: the radio section listens for ","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"VRKcxiPXkr"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"change","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"IRK3aCbJKl"},{"type":"text","value":" events and uses ","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"TUHUIHQdyq"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"document.querySelector('input[name=\"grp1\"]:checked')","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"fEIlZjBPAB"},{"type":"text","value":" to grab the one currently-selected radio and immediately print a message, while the checkbox section waits for a button click, uses ","position":{"start":{"line"